name: Deer Hunter print Gold pop Surrealism  Screen Print  Lowbrow  funky whimsical Art
description:
From the Deer Hunter editions, this print has a gold deer. 
The image of the deer is from a plastic deer head i found on the beast market in Huddersfield, in fact I have a small collection of them on my kitchen wall. 
 This hand made  Screen Print is inspired by the painting I did on Oldham st, Manchester as part of a  Lowbrow  Art gentrification show in the Northern Quarter of Manchester. The aim of the show was to mix funky Surrealism with street art and make the street my gallery. Painting Trophy Deer heads was perfect for this inside, outside, traditional art show, new street art, urban yet great outdoors mashup. This image draws on the history of hunting and trophies and collecting nature and is in itself a comment on perceptions of street art as wild and dangerous, are we on the wild frontier or in the streets of Manchester and whats the difference.     

LIMITED EDITION of 10 prints, 
numbered and signed by Trafford Parsons
Hand printed silk screen print on cartridge paper. 

Size: 70 x 50 cm.

All prints are sent out "Signed For", within 7 working days.

name: Marilyn 5. Pop Surrealism Lowbrow Pop Art Icon Celebrity
description:
Marilyn 5  
50 x 70 cm 
 editions of 10
On 5th august 2013 its 51 years since Marilyn died and became an imortal icon. One of the most ubiquitous images in pop art, these Marilyn 5  prints have been very popular and have now sold out the editions from last year.

 I very much wanted to overlay more screens this year to develop this print. The overlaying confuses the eye as to what screen to focus on, the smaller film stills or the big Marilyn or the  large number 5 that covers the print . The image becomes distressed yet perfectly recognisable as Marilyn Monroe. 

the print is one of the "In The Long Run We're All Dead" collection which  is a quote by John Maynard Keynes when asked about the future of the world bank in 1945.
i take this to mean we have today cos "in the long run we're all dead" - 'carpe diem'.. [sieze the day].

LIMITED EDITION OF 10 
Hand printed silk screen on paper, 
numbered & signed by Trafford Parsons 
Size: 50x 70cm

All prints are sent out "Signed For", within 7 working days.

name: Godzilla Gaia  at Tower Bridge  Pop Surreal SteamPunk High Quality Silkscreen Print Art Surrealism
description:
I think about this theme a lot "gaia" is planet earth.
Prints that look like film posters or stills from a B-movie. Inspired by Gaia theory, as expounded by a British Professor James Lovelock lends itself to my  love for sci-fi disaster movies and faux–science. Once I'd put these elements together the work just grew like a monster.
 
 Godzilla Gaia  at Tower Bridge is a still from a film that was never made.... 
Tower Bridge is the london landmark and finds its way into every film set in London.
 There is a very steam punk Victorian look to this bridge finished in 1894 yet its still a very vibrant part of contemporary London. And Godzilla is a great monster myth to work with and should make more movies for sure.
 
Prints like this are fuelled by  my interest in current affairs, not so much the agenda that gets into the mass media like police beating up students and cuts to the NHS, but the stuff that gets filtered out... 

"Are we a danger to the earth or is the earth a danger to us?"

LIMITED EDITION of 160 prints
Hand printed silk screen print on hand made paper. 

Size: 100 x 70 cm.

All prints are sent out "Signed For", within 7 working days.

name: "Art has left the Building" Lowbrow Pop Art ELVIS Icon rock n roll  Silk screen print
description:
Classic pop art icon ELVIS relaxing beneath the banner "Art has left the building", is a play on the end of an Elvis performance when the public address would proclaim Elvis has left the building to stop a riot as people tried to rush the backstage area... 

This image is saying "Art is the new rock n roll and has left the building". Pop art has left the alter of the high art gallery building and is in the street connecting with everyone on earth, just like Elvis. 
Rock n roll and pop art are two sides of the same coin, both disposable and eternal.

This image also makes a passing reference to the rise of street art and  advertising as art, being set out as a banner text and image.

The text is an epitaph as ELVIS's art has left us, but it can be taken or used as we see fit, I often say "Art has left the building" when I'm total happy with a piece of work and the job is finished.

Hand printed silk screen print on cartridge paper.

name: "Studies of a Skull"-left 120 degree View, LIMITED EDITION Screen Print Anatomical Lowbrow Art, C.T
description:
Part of a set of 6 studies which take views of a human skull in 60 degree stages round 360 degrees. These prints are based on C.T scans of a living woman and developed out of a collaboration with Bioteck 3D, the leading manufacturer of computer programmes that interpret C.T scans for hospitals. In this work my love of science  fiction becomes an investigation of science fact. This print also becomes a documentation of art as knowledge, information, facts and familiarity.

In turn these 6 prints are part of a larger body of work, a 4 year project that came to be known as "Something Wicked This Way Comes", all based on C.T scans of living people. 

"Studies of a Skull"- left 120 degree View
LIMITED EDITION of 100 prints, numbered and signed by Trafford Parsons
Hand printed silk screen print on cartridge paper. 

Size: 60 x 60 cm.

All prints are sent out "Signed For", within 7 working days.
